{"title_page": "Magdalena of Saxony", "text_new": "{{Unreferenced|date=December 2009}}\n{{Infobox royalty\n| title        = Electoral Princess of Brandeburg<br />Margravine of Brandenburg\n| name         = Duchess Magdalena of Saxony\n| full name    =\n| image        = Lucas Cranach d.\u00c4. - Bildnis der Magdalene von Sachsen (Art Institute of Chicago).jpg\n| image_size   =\n| caption      =\n| predecessor  =\n| successor    =\n| spouse       = [[Joachim II Hector, Elector of Brandenburg]]\n| issue        = [[John George, Elector of Brandenburg]]<br>[[Barbara of Brandenburg, Duchess of Brieg|Barbara]]<br>Elisabeth<br>[[Frederick of Brandenburg (1530\u20131552)|Friedrich, Archbishop of Magdeburg]]<br>Albrecht<br>Georg<br>Paul\n| house        = [[House of Wettin|Wettin]]\n| father       = [[George, Duke of Saxony]]\n| mother       = [[Barbara Jagiellon]]\n| birth_date   = 7 March 1507\n| birth_place  = [[Dresden]]\n| death_date   = {{Death date and age|1534|01|25|1507|03|07|df=y}}\n| death_place  =\n| burial_place =\n}}\n'''Magdalena of Saxony''' (7 March 1507 \u2013 25 January 1534) was Margravine of Brandenburg, its \"Electoral Princess\", the Electoral equivalent of a crown princess.\n\nShe was the daughter of [[George, Duke of Saxony|George ''the Bearded'', Duke of Saxony]] and his wife [[Barbara Jagiellon|Barbara]]. Magdalena's maternal grandparents were [[Kazimierz IV Jagiellon]] and his wife queen [[Elisabeth of Austria (1436\u20131505)|Elisabeth of Austria]], daughter of [[Albert II of Germany]].\n\nShe was a granddaughter of the Elisabeth aforementioned, mother of the [[Jagiellonians]], queen of Poland, who had claimed the [[Duchy of Luxembourg]] in 1460s as being the younger daughter of the last Luxembourg heiress [[Elisabeth of Luxembourg, Queen of Bohemia]]. Though by no means an heiress of her grandmother, she was intended to wed the heir of her grandmother's older sister. Joachim (1505\u20131571), the future elector of Brandenburg, was the eldest son and heir of their current claimant of Luxembourg, [[Joachim I, Elector of Brandenburg]] (1484\u20131535), the eldest son and heir of [[Margaret of Thuringia]] (1449\u20131501), Dowager Electress of Brandenburg, herself the eldest daughter and heiress of [[Anna, Duchess of Luxembourg]] and [[William of Saxony, Landgrave of Thuringia]].\n\nMagdalena was thus married, at [[Dresden]], on 6 November 1524, to her second cousin's son [[Joachim II of Brandenburg|Joachim]] Hector, the future Elector of Brandenburg. Their son was [[John George, Elector of Brandenburg|John George]], another future Elector of Brandenburg. After Magdalena's death which occurred well before Joachim ascended the electorate, Joachim II Hector married [[Hedwig Jagiellon (1513\u20131573)|Hedwig Jagiellon]], daughter of King [[Sigismund I the Old|Sigismund I of Poland]].\n\nMagdalena and Joachim II Hector had issue:\n* [[John George, Elector of Brandenburg]] (1525\u20131598), had issue\n* [[Barbara of Brandenburg, Duchess of Brieg]] (1527\u20131595), had issue\n* Elisabeth (1528\u20131529)\n* [[Frederick IV of Brandenburg]] (1530\u20131552), [[Archbishop of Magdeburg]] and [[Bishop of Halberstadt]]\n* Albrecht (1532\u20131532)\n* Georg (1532\u20131532)\n* Paul (1534\u20131534)\n\n{{ahnentafel\n|collapsed=yes |align=center\n|boxstyle_1=background-color: #fcc;\n|boxstyle_2=background-color: #fb9;\n|boxstyle_3=background-color: #ffc;\n|boxstyle_4=background-color: #bfc;\n|boxstyle_5=background-color: #9fe;\n|1= 1. '''Magdalena of Saxony'''\n|2= 2. [[George, Duke of Saxony]]\n|3= 3. [[Barbara Jagiellon]]\n|4= 4. [[Albert III, Duke of Saxony]]\n|5= 5. [[Sidonie of Pod\u011bbrady]]\n|6= 6. [[Casimir IV Jagiellon]]\n|7= 7. [[Elisabeth of Austria (1436\u20131505)|Elisabeth of Austria]]\n|8= 8. [[Frederick II, Elector of Saxony]]\n|9= 9. [[Margaret of Austria, Electress of Saxony|Margarete of Austria]]\n|10= 10. [[George of Pod\u011bbrady]]\n|11= 11. [[Kunigunde of Sternberg]]\n|12= 12. [[Jogaila|W\u0142adys\u0142aw II Jagie\u0142\u0142o]]\n|13= 13. [[Sophia of Halshany]]\n|14= 14. [[Albert II of Germany]]\n|15= 15. [[Elizabeth of Luxembourg]]\n|16= 16. [[Frederick I, Elector of Saxony]]\n|17= 17. Catherine of Brunswick-L\u00fcneburg\n|18= 18. [[Ernest, Duke of Austria]]\n|19= 19. [[Cymburgis of Masovia]]\n|20= 20. [[Victor of Kun\u0161t\u00e1t and Pod\u011bbrady]]\n|21= 21. Anna of Wartenberg\n|22= 22. Smil of Sternberg\n|23= 23. Barbara of Pardubice \n|24= 24. [[Algirdas|Algirdas of Lithuania]]\n|25= 25. [[Uliana of Tver]]\n|26= 26. Andrew of Halshany\n|27= 27. Alexandra Drucka\n|28= 28. [[Albert IV, Duke of Austria]]\n|29= 29. [[Joanna Sophia of Bavaria|Johanna Sophia of Bavaria]]\n|30= 30. [[Sigismund, Holy Roman Emperor]]\n|31= 31. [[Barbara of Cilli]]\n}}\n\n{{Princesses of Saxony}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Magdalena Of Saxony, Duchess}}\n[[Category:House of Wettin]]\n[[Category:People from Dresden]]\n[[Category:1507 births]]\n[[Category:1534 deaths]]\n[[Category:Electoral Princesses of Brandenburg]]\n[[Category:Margravines of Germany]]\n[[Category:Albertine branch]]\n", "text_old": "{{Unreferenced|date=December 2009}}\n{{Infobox royalty\n| title        = Electoral Princess of Brandeburg<br />Margravine of Brandenburg\n| name         = Duchess Magdalena of Saxony\n| full name    =\n| image        = Lucas Cranach d.\u00c4. - Bildnis der Magdalene von Sachsen (Art Institute of Chicago).jpg\n| image_size   =\n| caption      =\n| predecessor  =\n| successor    =\n| spouse       = [[Joachim II Hector, Elector of Brandenburg]]\n| issue        = [[John George, Elector of Brandenburg]]<br>[[Barbara of Brandenburg, Duchess of Brieg|Barbara]]<br>Elisabeth<br>Friedrich, Archbishop of Magdeburg<br>Albrecht<br>Georg<br>Paul\n| house        = [[House of Wettin|Wettin]]\n| father       = [[George, Duke of Saxony]]\n| mother       = [[Barbara Jagiellon]]\n| birth_date   = 7 March 1507\n| birth_place  = [[Dresden]]\n| death_date   = {{Death date and age|1534|01|25|1507|03|07|df=y}}\n| death_place  =\n| burial_place =\n}}\n'''Magdalena of Saxony''' (7 March 1507 \u2013 25 January 1534) was Margravine of Brandenburg, its \"Electoral Princess\", the Electoral equivalent of a crown princess.\n\nShe was the daughter of [[George, Duke of Saxony|George ''the Bearded'', Duke of Saxony]] and his wife [[Barbara Jagiellon|Barbara]]. Magdalena's maternal grandparents were [[Kazimierz IV Jagiellon]] and his wife queen [[Elisabeth of Austria (1436\u20131505)|Elisabeth of Austria]], daughter of [[Albert II of Germany]].\n\nShe was a granddaughter of the Elisabeth aforementioned, mother of the [[Jagiellonians]], queen of Poland, who had claimed the [[Duchy of Luxembourg]] in 1460s as being the younger daughter of the last Luxembourg heiress [[Elisabeth of Luxembourg, Queen of Bohemia]]. Though by no means an heiress of her grandmother, she was intended to wed the heir of her grandmother's older sister. Joachim (1505\u20131571), the future elector of Brandenburg, was the eldest son and heir of their current claimant of Luxembourg, [[Joachim I, Elector of Brandenburg]] (1484\u20131535), the eldest son and heir of [[Margaret of Thuringia]] (1449\u20131501), Dowager Electress of Brandenburg, herself the eldest daughter and heiress of [[Anna, Duchess of Luxembourg]] and [[William of Saxony, Landgrave of Thuringia]].\n\nMagdalena was thus married, at [[Dresden]], on 6 November 1524, to her second cousin's son [[Joachim II of Brandenburg|Joachim]] Hector, the future Elector of Brandenburg. Their son was [[John George, Elector of Brandenburg|John George]], another future Elector of Brandenburg. After Magdalena's death which occurred well before Joachim ascended the electorate, Joachim II Hector married [[Hedwig Jagiellon (1513\u20131573)|Hedwig Jagiellon]], daughter of King [[Sigismund I the Old|Sigismund I of Poland]].\n\nMagdalena and Joachim II Hector had issue:\n* [[John George, Elector of Brandenburg]] (1525\u20131598), had issue\n* [[Barbara of Brandenburg, Duchess of Brieg]] (1527\u20131595), had issue\n* Elisabeth (1528\u20131529)\n* [[Frederick IV of Brandenburg]] (1530\u20131552), [[Archbishop of Magdeburg]] and [[Bishop of Halberstadt]]\n* Albrecht (1532\u20131532)\n* Georg (1532\u20131532)\n* Paul (1534\u20131534)\n\n{{ahnentafel\n|collapsed=yes |align=center\n|boxstyle_1=background-color: #fcc;\n|boxstyle_2=background-color: #fb9;\n|boxstyle_3=background-color: #ffc;\n|boxstyle_4=background-color: #bfc;\n|boxstyle_5=background-color: #9fe;\n|1= 1. '''Magdalena of Saxony'''\n|2= 2. [[George, Duke of Saxony]]\n|3= 3. [[Barbara Jagiellon]]\n|4= 4. [[Albert III, Duke of Saxony]]\n|5= 5. [[Sidonie of Pod\u011bbrady]]\n|6= 6. [[Casimir IV Jagiellon]]\n|7= 7. [[Elisabeth of Austria (1436\u20131505)|Elisabeth of Austria]]\n|8= 8. [[Frederick II, Elector of Saxony]]\n|9= 9. [[Margaret of Austria, Electress of Saxony|Margarete of Austria]]\n|10= 10. [[George of Pod\u011bbrady]]\n|11= 11. [[Kunigunde of Sternberg]]\n|12= 12. [[Jogaila|W\u0142adys\u0142aw II Jagie\u0142\u0142o]]\n|13= 13. [[Sophia of Halshany]]\n|14= 14. [[Albert II of Germany]]\n|15= 15. [[Elizabeth of Luxembourg]]\n|16= 16. [[Frederick I, Elector of Saxony]]\n|17= 17. Catherine of Brunswick-L\u00fcneburg\n|18= 18. [[Ernest, Duke of Austria]]\n|19= 19. [[Cymburgis of Masovia]]\n|20= 20. [[Victor of Kun\u0161t\u00e1t and Pod\u011bbrady]]\n|21= 21. Anna of Wartenberg\n|22= 22. Smil of Sternberg\n|23= 23. Barbara of Pardubice \n|24= 24. [[Algirdas|Algirdas of Lithuania]]\n|25= 25. [[Uliana of Tver]]\n|26= 26. Andrew of Halshany\n|27= 27. Alexandra Drucka\n|28= 28. [[Albert IV, Duke of Austria]]\n|29= 29. [[Joanna Sophia of Bavaria|Johanna Sophia of Bavaria]]\n|30= 30. [[Sigismund, Holy Roman Emperor]]\n|31= 31. [[Barbara of Cilli]]\n}}\n\n{{Princesses of Saxony}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Magdalena Of Saxony, Duchess}}\n[[Category:House of Wettin]]\n[[Category:People from Dresden]]\n[[Category:1507 births]]\n[[Category:1534 deaths]]\n[[Category:Electoral Princesses of Brandenburg]]\n[[Category:Margravines of Germany]]\n[[Category:Albertine branch]]\n", "name_user": "ArisMethymna", "label": "safe", "comment": "a link is added to infobox", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magdalena_of_Saxony"}
{"title_page": "Ovarian reserve", "text_new": "[[Image:WallaceKelseyModel.jpg|thumb|right|420px|Model of ovarian reserve from conception to the menopause]]'''Ovarian reserve''' is a term that is used to determine the capacity of the [[ovary]] to provide [[egg cell]]s that are capable of [[fertilization]] resulting in a healthy and successful [[pregnancy]]. With [[advanced maternal age]] the number of egg cell that can be successfully recruited for a possible pregnancy declines, constituting a major factor in the inverse correlation between [[age and female fertility]].\n\nWhile there is no known method for assessing the ovarian reserve of individual women,<ref>{{cite journal | author = Broekemans FJ | display-authors = etal | year = 1998 | title = Ovarian reserve tests in infertility practice and normal fertile women. | url = | journal = Maturitas | volume = 30 | issue = 2| pages = 205\u201314 }}</ref> indirect determination of ovarian reserve is important in the treatment of [[infertility]].<ref>{{cite journal | author = Broekemans FJ | display-authors = etal | year = 2006 | title = A systematic review of tests predicting ovarian reserve and IVF outcome. | url = | journal = Hum Reprod Update | volume = 12 | issue = 6| pages = 685\u2013718 }}</ref>\n\n==Establishment==\nThe ovary is generally thought of as an egg bank from which the woman draws during her reproductive life. The human ovary contains a population of [[primordial follicle]]s. At 18\u201322 weeks post-conception, the female [[ovary]] contains its peak number of follicles (about 300,000 in the average case, but individual peak populations range from 35,000 to 2.5 million<ref name=\"WKmodel\">{{cite journal | author = Wallace WHB, Kelsey TW | year = 2010 | title = Human Ovarian Reserve from Conception to the Menopause | url = http://dx.plos.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0008772 | journal = PLoS ONE | volume = 5 | issue = 1| page = e8772 | doi = 10.1371/journal.pone.0008772 }}</ref>).\n\nThe size of the initial ovarian reserve is strongly influenced by [[genetics]].<ref name=\"RichardsonGuo2013\"/> Also, elevated [[androgen]] levels during [[prenatal development]] have an adverse effect on the early establishment of the ovarian reserve.<ref name=\"RichardsonGuo2013\">{{cite journal|last1=Richardson|first1=M. C.|last2=Guo|first2=M.|last3=Fauser|first3=B. C. J. M.|last4=Macklon|first4=N. S.|title=Environmental and developmental origins of ovarian reserve|journal=Human Reproduction Update|volume=20|issue=3|year=2013|pages=353\u2013369|issn=1355-4786|doi=10.1093/humupd/dmt057}}</ref>\n\nThe ovarian reserve is at maximum value in sixth month old embryos. Then this amount is only decreasing, as there is no new synthesis and differentiation. There is a huge decrease before the child is born, being this pool reduced from over 8 millions potential oocytes to 2 millions. The amount continues decreasing progressively until reaching the age of 30 years old, in which there is a dramatically decrease. \n\nThere are about 1 to 2 million oocytes when a woman is born. From them, 400000 oocytes will reach the stage of puberty and only 400 will rise maturation and ovulation. The rest of them reach [[Ovarian follicle atresia|atresia]], a natural apoptotic process leading to the breakdown of the follicle.\n\n==Decline==\nEach [[menstrual cycle]] one egg cell is released by ovulation. In addition, the remaining follicles that were recruited towards maturation are lost by [[Ovarian follicle atresia|atresia]]. Few if any egg cells are replenished during the reproductive years. However, this loss by the [[menstrual cycle]] only accounts for approximately up to 10 egg cells per month, thus accounting for only a small fraction of the actual loss of egg cells throughout the lifetime.\n\nOne additional contributory mechanism for the decline in the ovarian reserve with age appears to be a decreased [[gene expression]] of proteins involved in [[DNA repair]] by [[homologous recombination]] such as [[BRCA1]], [[MRE11]], [[Rad51]] and [[Ataxia telangiectasia mutated|ATM]].<ref name=Titus>{{cite journal | author = Titus S, Li F, Stobezki R, Akula K, Unsal E, Jeong K, Dickler M, Robson M, Moy F, Goswami S, Oktay K | year = 2013 | title = Impairment of BRCA1-related DNA double-strand break repair leads to ovarian aging in mice and humans | journal = Sci Transl Med | volume = 5 | issue = | page = 172ra21| doi = 10.1126/scitranslmed.3004925 | pmid = 23408054 | pmc = 5130338 }}</ref>\n\n==Assessment==\nWomen who are 35 years or older who have attempted to get pregnant unsuccessfully for 6 months should undergo testing for ovarian reserve. The most commonly used test to assess this ovarian reserve is the ''day 3 FSH test''.<ref>Scott RT et al. (1989) ''Follicle stimulating hormone levels on cycle day 3 are predictive of in vitro fertilization outcome.'' Fertility and Sterility. 1989; 51:651-4.</ref> This blood test determines the level of [[follicle-stimulating hormone|FSH]] on cycle day 3. Cycle day 3 is chosen because at this time the [[estrogen]] level is expected to be low, a critical feature, as FSH levels are subject to a [[negative feedback]].\nThus any determination of FSH needs to include the corresponding [[estradiol]] level to indicate that the FSH level was drawn when the estrogen level was low. In a patient with infrequent menstruation, an FSH level and estrogen level could be measured at random and is valid if the estrogen level is low. Generally FSH levels are expected to be below 10 [[international unit|miu]]/ml in women with reproductive potential (levels of 10-15 miu/ml are considered borderline), however the exact numbers returned will depend on the type of assay used in a particular laboratory. \n\nAlthough FSH and more recently Inhibin B have been shown to have some correlation with ovarian reserve, it is now well established that Anti-Mullerian Hormone or AMH is more useful biochemical test.{{Citation needed|date=December 2017}} High levels however can be present in women with Polycystic Ovarian Syndrome which compromises female fertility and therefore a combination of AMH and a transvaginal ultrasound to count the number of antral follicles is probably the best way to assess ovarian reserve and future fertility. This combination is sometimes referred to as the Biological Body Clock Test.{{Citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\nA [[clomiphene]] challenge test is a variation on this approach.<ref>{{cite journal | author = | year = 2003 | title = Use of clomiphene citrate in women | url = | journal = Fertil Steril | volume = 80 | issue = | pages = 1302\u20131308 | doi = 10.1016/s0015-0282(03)01184-1 }}</ref>\n\nAnother approach is to examine the ovaries by [[gynecologic ultrasonography]] and to determine their size as ovaries depleted of egg cells tend to be smaller<ref>Wallace WHB and Kelsey TW (2004)''Ovarian reserve and reproductive age may be determined from measurement of ovarian volume by transvaginal sonography.'' Human Reproduction; 19(7):1612-1617</ref> and to examine the number of antral follicles visible by sonography.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Kwee  | display-authors = etal | year = 2007 | title = Ovarian volume and antral follicle count for the prediction of low and hyper responders with in vitro fertilization. | url = | journal = Reprod Biol Endocrinol | volume = 5 | issue = | page = 9 | doi = 10.1186/1477-7827-5-9 }}</ref>\n\n===Implications===\nWomen with poor ovarian reserve are unlikely to conceive with infertility therapy. Also see [[poor ovarian reserve]] and [[Follicle-stimulating hormone]] for treatment options.\n\n==See also==\n*[[DNA damage (naturally occurring)]]\n*[[Folliculogenesis]]\n*[[Meiosis]]\n*[[Oogenesis]]\n*[[Ovary]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ovarian Reserve}}\n[[Category:Gynaecology]]\n[[Category:Reproduction in mammals]]\n", "text_old": "[[Image:WallaceKelseyModel.jpg|thumb|right|420px|Model of ovarian reserve from conception to the menopause]]'''Ovarian reserve''' is a term that is used to determine the capacity of the [[ovary]] to provide [[egg cell]]s that are capable of [[fertilization]] resulting in a healthy and successful [[pregnancy]]. With [[advanced maternal age]] the number of egg cell that can be successfully recruited for a possible pregnancy declines, constituting a major factor in the inverse correlation between [[age and female fertility]].\n\nWhile there is no known method for assessing the ovarian reserve of individual women,<ref>{{cite journal | author = Broekemans FJ | display-authors = etal | year = 1998 | title = Ovarian reserve tests in infertility practice and normal fertile women. | url = | journal = Maturitas | volume = 30 | issue = 2| pages = 205\u201314 }}</ref> indirect determination of ovarian reserve is important in the treatment of [[infertility]].<ref>{{cite journal | author = Broekemans FJ | display-authors = etal | year = 2006 | title = A systematic review of tests predicting ovarian reserve and IVF outcome. | url = | journal = Hum Reprod Update | volume = 12 | issue = 6| pages = 685\u2013718 }}</ref>\n\n==Establishment==\nThe ovary is generally thought of as an egg bank from which the woman draws during her reproductive life. The human ovary contains a population of [[primordial follicle]]s. At 18\u201322 weeks post-conception, the female [[ovary]] contains its peak number of follicles (about 300,000 in the average case, but individual peak populations range from 35,000 to 2.5 million<ref name=\"WKmodel\">{{cite journal | author = Wallace WHB, Kelsey TW | year = 2010 | title = Human Ovarian Reserve from Conception to the Menopause | url = http://dx.plos.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0008772 | journal = PLoS ONE | volume = 5 | issue = 1| page = e8772 | doi = 10.1371/journal.pone.0008772 }}</ref>).\n\nThe size of the initial ovarian reserve is strongly influenced by [[genetics]].<ref name=\"RichardsonGuo2013\"/> Also, elevated [[androgen]] levels during [[prenatal development]] have an adverse effect on the early establishment of the ovarian reserve.<ref name=\"RichardsonGuo2013\">{{cite journal|last1=Richardson|first1=M. C.|last2=Guo|first2=M.|last3=Fauser|first3=B. C. J. M.|last4=Macklon|first4=N. S.|title=Environmental and developmental origins of ovarian reserve|journal=Human Reproduction Update|volume=20|issue=3|year=2013|pages=353\u2013369|issn=1355-4786|doi=10.1093/humupd/dmt057}}</ref>\n\nThe ovarian reserve is at maximum value in sixth month old embryos. Then this amount is only decreasing, as there is no new synthesis and differentiation. There is a huge decrease before the child is born, being this pool reduced from over 8 millions potential oocytes to 2 millions. The amount continues decreasing progressively until reaching the age of 30 years old, in which there is a dramatically decrease. \n\nThere are about 1 to 2 million oocytes when a woman is born. From them, 400000 oocytes will reach the stage of puberty and only 400 will rise maturation and ovulation. The rest of them reach [[Ovarian follicle atresia|atresia]], a natural apoptotic process leading to the breakdown of the follicle.\n\n==Decline==\nEach [[menstrual cycle]] one egg cell is released by ovulation. In addition, the remaining follicles that were recruited towards maturation are lost by [[Ovarian follicle atresia|atresia]]. Few if any egg cells are replenished during the reproductive years. However, this loss by the [[menstrual cycle]] only accounts for approximately up to 10 egg cells per month, thus accounting for only a small fraction of the actual loss of egg cells throughout the lifetime.\n\nOne additional contributory mechanism for the decline in the ovarian reserve with age appears to be a decreased [[gene expression]] of proteins involved in [[DNA repair]] by [[homologous recombination]] such as [[BRCA1]], [[MRE11]], [[Rad51]] and [[Ataxia telangiectasia mutated|ATM]].<ref name=Titus>Titus S, Li F, Stobezki R, Akula K, Unsal E, Jeong K, Dickler M, Robson M, Moy F, Goswami S, Oktay K. (2013). Impairment of BRCA1-related DNA double-strand break repair leads to ovarian aging in mice and humans. Sci Transl Med 5(172):172ra21. doi: 10.1126/scitranslmed.3004925. {{PMID|23408054}}</ref>\n\n==Assessment==\nWomen who are 35 years or older who have attempted to get pregnant unsuccessfully for 6 months should undergo testing for ovarian reserve. The most commonly used test to assess this ovarian reserve is the ''day 3 FSH test''.<ref>Scott RT et al. (1989) ''Follicle stimulating hormone levels on cycle day 3 are predictive of in vitro fertilization outcome.'' Fertility and Sterility. 1989; 51:651-4.</ref> This blood test determines the level of [[follicle-stimulating hormone|FSH]] on cycle day 3. Cycle day 3 is chosen because at this time the [[estrogen]] level is expected to be low, a critical feature, as FSH levels are subject to a [[negative feedback]].\nThus any determination of FSH needs to include the corresponding [[estradiol]] level to indicate that the FSH level was drawn when the estrogen level was low. In a patient with infrequent menstruation, an FSH level and estrogen level could be measured at random and is valid if the estrogen level is low. Generally FSH levels are expected to be below 10 [[international unit|miu]]/ml in women with reproductive potential (levels of 10-15 miu/ml are considered borderline), however the exact numbers returned will depend on the type of assay used in a particular laboratory. \n\nAlthough FSH and more recently Inhibin B have been shown to have some correlation with ovarian reserve, it is now well established that Anti-Mullerian Hormone or AMH is more useful biochemical test.{{Citation needed|date=December 2017}} High levels however can be present in women with Polycystic Ovarian Syndrome which compromises female fertility and therefore a combination of AMH and a transvaginal ultrasound to count the number of antral follicles is probably the best way to assess ovarian reserve and future fertility. This combination is sometimes referred to as the Biological Body Clock Test.{{Citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\nA [[clomiphene]] challenge test is a variation on this approach.<ref>{{cite journal | author = | year = 2003 | title = Use of clomiphene citrate in women | url = | journal = Fertil Steril | volume = 80 | issue = | page = 1302 | doi = 10.1016/s0015-0282(03)01184-1 }}</ref>\n\nAnother approach is to examine the ovaries by [[gynecologic ultrasonography]] and to determine their size as ovaries depleted of egg cells tend to be smaller<ref>Wallace WHB and Kelsey TW (2004)''Ovarian reserve and reproductive age may be determined from measurement of ovarian volume by transvaginal sonography.'' Human Reproduction; 19(7):1612-1617</ref> and to examine the number of antral follicles visible by sonography.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Kwee  | display-authors = etal | year = 2007 | title = Ovarian volume and antral follicle count for the prediction of low and hyper responders with in vitro fertilization. | url = | journal = Reprod Biol Endocrinol | volume = 5 | issue = | page = 9 | doi = 10.1186/1477-7827-5-9 }}</ref>\n\n===Implications===\nWomen with poor ovarian reserve are unlikely to conceive with infertility therapy. Also see [[poor ovarian reserve]] and [[Follicle-stimulating hormone]] for treatment options.\n\n==See also==\n*[[DNA damage (naturally occurring)]]\n*[[Folliculogenesis]]\n*[[Meiosis]]\n*[[Oogenesis]]\n*[[Ovary]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ovarian Reserve}}\n[[Category:Gynaecology]]\n[[Category:Reproduction in mammals]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "Journal cites:, completed 1 page range", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ovarian_reserve"}
{"title_page": "Phan Chali", "text_new": "{{unref}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n<!--See the Table at Infobox Settlement for all fields and descriptions of usage-->\n<!-- Basic info  ---------------->\n|official_name          = Phan Chali\n|other_name             = \n|native_name            = \u0e1e\u0e31\u0e19\u0e0a\u0e32\u0e25\u0e35\n|nickname               = \n|settlement_type        = Tambon\n|motto                  =\n<!-- images and maps  ----------->\n|image_skyline          = \n|imagesize              = \n|image_caption          = \n|image_flag             = \n|flag_size              =\n|image_seal             = \n|seal_size              =\n|image_map              = \n|mapsize                = \n|map_caption            = \n|image_map1             = \n|mapsize1               = \n|map_caption1           = \n<!-- Location ------------------>\n|subdivision_type3     = District\n|subdivision_name3     = [[Wang Thong]]\n|subdivision_type2      = Province\n|subdivision_name2      = [[Phitsanulok Province|Phitsanulok]]\n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = [[Thailand]]\n<!-- Politics ----------------->\n|government_footnotes   =\n|government_type        = \n|leader_title           = \n|leader_name            = \n|established_title      = \n|established_date       = \n|established_title2     = \n|established_date2      = \n|established_title3     =\n|established_date3      =\n<!-- Area    --------------------->\n|area_footnotes           =\n|area_total_km2           = \n|area_water_km2           =\n|area_water_percent       =\n|area_urban_km2           =\n|area_metro_km2           =\n|area_blank1_title        =\n|area_blank1_km2          =\n<!-- Population   ----------------------->\n|population_as_of               = 2005\n|population_footnotes           = \n|population_note                = \n|population_total               = 9873\n|population_density_km2         = \n|population_metro               =\n|population_density_metro_km2   =\n|population_urban               =\n|population_density_urban_km2   =\n|population_blank1_title        =\n|population_blank1              =\n|population_density_blank1_km2 =   \n<!-- General information  --------------->\n|timezone               = [[Time in Thailand|ICT]]\n|utc_offset             = +7\n|coordinates            = {{coord|16|38|00|N|100|29|00|E|region:TH|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation_footnotes    =  \n|elevation_m            = \n<!-- Area/postal codes & others -------->\n|postal_code_type       = Postal code\n|postal_code            = 65130\n|area_code              =\n|blank_name             = Geocode\n|blank_info             = 650802\n|blank1_name            =\n|blank1_info            =\n|website                =  \n|footnotes              = \n}}\n\n'''Phan Chali''' ({{lang-th|\u0e1e\u0e31\u0e19\u0e0a\u0e32\u0e25\u0e35}}) is a sub-district in the [[Wang Thong District]] of [[Phitsanulok Province]], [[Thailand]].\n\n==Geography==\nPhan Chali lies in the [[Nan River#Nan Basin|Nan Basin]], which is part of the [[Chao Phraya River#Chao Phraya watershed|Chao Phraya Watershed]].\n\n==Administration==\nThe sub-district is divided into 17 smaller divisions called (''[[muban]]''), which roughly correspond to the villages. There are 15 villages, several of which occupy more than one muban. Phan Chali is administered by a [[tambon administrative organization]] (TAO). The muban in Phan Chali are enumerated as follows:\n<ref name=\"Pitlocal.org\">[http://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:GX9UMhZNdisJ:www.pitloklocal.org/songko47.xls+%E0%B9%82%E0%B8%81%E0%B8%A3%E0%B8%87%E0%B9%80%E0%B8%81%E0%B8%A3%E0%B8%87&hl=en&ct=clnk&cd=7&gl=us Pitlocal.org] (Thai){{DL}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| No.\n| English\n| Thai\n|-\n| 1\n| Ban Rai Phan Chali (Ban Phan Chali Farm)\n| \u0e1a\u0e49\u0e32\u0e19\u0e44\u0e23\u0e48\u0e1e\u0e31\u0e19\u0e0a\u0e32\u0e25\u0e35\n|-\n| 2\n| Ban Phan Chali (part)\n| \u0e1a\u0e49\u0e32\u0e19\u0e1e\u0e31\u0e19\u0e0a\u0e32\u0e25\u0e35\n|-\n