{"title_page": "The Mothman Prophecies (film)", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Mothman Prophecies\n| image          = Mothman prophecies poster.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Mark Pellington]]\n| producer       = [[Gary W. Goldstein]]<br />[[Gary Lucchesi]]<br />[[Tom Rosenberg]]\n| screenplay     = [[Richard Hatem]]\n| based on       = ''[[The Mothman Prophecies]]'' by [[John Keel]]\n| starring       = [[Richard Gere]]<br />[[Laura Linney]]<br />[[Will Patton]]<br />[[Debra Messing]]<br />[[Lucinda Jenney]]<br />[[Alan Bates]]\n| music          = [[Cliff Eidelman]]<br />[[tomandandy]]\n| cinematography = Fred Murphy\n| editing        = [[Brian Berdan]]\n| studio         = [[Lakeshore Entertainment]] \n| distributor    = [[Screen Gems]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2002|1|25}}\n| runtime        = 119 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $32 million<ref name=BoxOfficeMojo>{{cite web |url=https://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=mothmanprophecies.htm |title=The Mothman Prophecies (2002)|publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=2013-02-06}}</ref>\n| gross          = $55.1 million<ref name=\"BoxOfficeMojo\"/>\n}}\n\n'''''The Mothman Prophecies''''' is a 2002 American [[supernatural horror]]-[[mystery film]] directed by [[Mark Pellington]], and starring [[Richard Gere]] and [[Laura Linney]]. Based on the 1975 [[The Mothman Prophecies|book of the same name]] by [[parapsychology|parapsychologist]] and [[Charles Fort|Fortean]] author [[John Keel]], the screenplay was written by [[Richard Hatem]]. \n\nThe story follows John Klein (Gere), a reporter who researches the legend of the [[Mothman]]. Still shaken by the death of his wife, two years earlier in a mysterious accident. Klein is sent to cover a news piece and ends up inexplicably finding himself in [[Point Pleasant, West Virginia]], where there have been sightings of an unusual creature and other unexplained phenomena. As he becomes increasingly drawn into mysterious forces at work, he hopes they can reconnect him to his wife, while the local sheriff (Linney) becomes concerned about his obsessions.\n\nThe film claims to be based on actual events that occurred between November 1966 and December 1967 in Point Pleasant, as described by Keel. It was shot in  [[Pittsburgh]] and [[Kittanning, Pennsylvania]] and was released to mixed reviews.\n\n==Plot==\n''[[Washington Post]]'' columnist John Klein and his wife Mary are involved in an accident when Mary swerves to avoid a black, flying figure. John survives the crash unscathed, but Mary is hospitalized. After Mary dies of an unrelated [[glioblastoma|brain tumor]], John discovers mysterious drawings of the creature that she had created & materialscientist is gay whilst in hospital.\n\nTwo years later, John becomes lost in [[West Virginia]] and inexplicably finds himself in [[Point Pleasant, West Virginia|Point Pleasant]], hundreds of miles off his route. Driving in the middle of the night, his car breaks down; and he walks to a nearby house to get help. The owner, Gordon Smallwood, reacts violently to John's appearance and holds him at gunpoint. Local police officer Connie Mills defuses the situation while Gordon explains that this is the third consecutive night John has knocked on his door at 2:30 AM, asking to use a phone, much to John's confusion. John stays at a local motel and considers how he ended up so far from his original destination.\n\nOfficer Mills mentions to John that many strange things have been occurring in the past few weeks and that people report seeing a large winged creature like a giant [[moth]] with red eyes. She also tells John about a strange dream she had, in which the words \"Wake up, Number 37\" were spoken to her. During a conversation one day, Gordon reveals to John that he has heard voices coming from his sink telling him that, in [[Denver]], \"99 will die\". While discussing the day's events at a local diner, John notices that the news is showing the story of an airplane crash in Denver that killed all 99 passengers aboard. The next night Gordon frantically explains that the voices in his head emanate from a being named Indrid Cold.\n\nLater that night Gordon calls John and says that he is standing next to someone named Indrid Cold. While John keeps Cold on the line, Officer Mills checks on Gordon. Cold answers John's questions, including ones he could not possibly know the answers to, convincing John that Cold is a supernatural being. This episode starts a string of supernatural calls to John's motel room. One tells him that there will be a great tragedy on the [[Ohio River]]. Later John receives a call from Gordon and rushes to his home to check on him. He finds Gordon outside, dead from [[Hypothermia|exposure]].\n\nJohn becomes obsessed with the being dubbed the Mothman. He meets an expert on the subject, Alexander Leek, who explains its nature and discourages John from becoming further involved. However, when John learns the [[Governor of West Virginia|Governor]] plans to tour a chemical plant located on the Ohio River the following day, he becomes convinced the tragedy will occur there. Officer Mills and the governor ignore his warnings, and nothing happens during the tour. Soon afterwards, John receives a mysterious message that instructs him to await a call from his deceased wife Mary back in [[Georgetown (Washington, D.C.)|Georgetown]], and he returns home.\n\nOn [[Christmas Eve]], Officer Mills calls and convinces him to ignore the phone call from \"Mary\", return to Point Pleasant, and join her. Though anguished, John agrees. As John reaches the [[Silver Bridge]], a malfunctioning traffic light causes traffic congestion. As John walks onto the bridge to investigate, the bolts and supports of the bridge strain. The bridge comes apart, and John realizes that the prophesied tragedy on the Ohio River was about the bridge. As the bridge collapses, Officer Mills' car falls into the water. John jumps in after her and pulls her from the river and up to safety. As the two sit on the back of an ambulance, they see that 36 people have been killed, making Connie the \"number 37\" from her dream. The cause of the bridge collapse was never fully determined. Although the Mothman has been sighted in other parts of the world, it was never seen again in Point Pleasant.\n\n==Cast==\n[[File:Richardgere.jpg|thumb|upright|right|Lead actor Richard Gere who portrayed the protagonist John Klein.]]\n* [[Richard Gere]] as John Klein\n* [[Laura Linney]] as Connie Mills\n* [[Will Patton]] as Gordon Smallwood\n* [[Debra Messing]] as Mary Klein\n* [[Lucinda Jenney]] as Denise Smallwood\n* [[Alan Bates]] as Alexander Leek\n* [[David Eigenberg]] as Ed Fleischman\n* Bob Tracey as Cyrus Bills\n* [[Mark Pellington]] as Indrid Cold \"The Mothman\" (voice)\n\n==Themes and interpretations==\n[[File:Mothman2.jpg |200px |left |thumb |Film critics have interpreted the film's portrayal of [[Mothman]] as demonic.]]\nWriter Paul Meehan judged the film's explanation of the Mothman to be a \"confused mish-mosh of [[science fiction]] and [[demonology]]\" and likened it to the television series ''[[The X-Files]]'', though preserving Keel's \"breathless hysteria\".{{sfn|Meehan|2009|p=130}} Meehan remarked that \"Aliens spouting prophetic utterances are rare in UFO literature\".{{sfn|Meehan|2009|p=130}}\n\nIn contrast to Meehan, author Jason Horsley declared ''The Mothman Prophecies'' \"probably the most effective depiction of demonic forces at work\" in U.S. cinema.{{sfn|Horsley|2009|p=197}} Horsley assessed its approach to the Mothman legend as depicting a \"schizophrenic nature of reality\", fulfilling a \"revelation\" purpose in [[horror film]], as it \"strips away the comfortable veneer of consensus reality to reveal the seething abyss of irrationality\".{{sfn|Horsley|2009|p=197}} Horsley argued the film's Mothman arrives from a foreign dimension, but being without \"physical existence\", it is also a product of the minds of Point Pleasant's citizens, based on \"formless and impersonal energy\".{{sfn|Horsley|2009|p=198}} The Mothman, identified by Horsley as \"emissary of the [[Id, ego and super-ego|Id]]\", is depicted in the film as being as natural as electricity or gravity.{{sfn|Horsley|2009|p=198}}\n\n==Production==\n[[Carl Franklin]] was originally attached to direct Richard Hatem's [[spec script]] before [[Mark Pellington]] was hired.<ref>{{cite news|author=Petrikin, Chris|title=Fox puts Armitage in Doud\u2019s \u2018Body\u2019|url=https://variety.com/1999/film/news/fox-puts-armitage-in-doud-s-body-1117500041/|work=Variety|date=May 5, 1999|accessdate=July 25, 2015}}</ref> Pellington rejected numerous screenplay drafts as literal interpretations of Keel's book, and wished to explore psychological drama in UFO witnesses.<ref name=\"Rickard\">{{cite web|last=Rickard |first=Bob |title=The moth man cometh |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2002/feb/22/artsfeatures3 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=February 22, 2002 |accessdate=August 23, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn reality, 46 people died in the collapse of the [[Silver Bridge]], not 36 as depicted in the film. The motion picture's claim at the end credits of the collapse of the Silver Bridge never being explained is false; the incident was found to be caused by the failure of an [[Eyebar|eye-bar]] in a suspension chain in 1971, well before the publication of the book on which the film is based, let alone the film.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.ca/newspapers?id=cJ1eAAAAIBAJ&sjid=MVMNAAAAIBAJ&pg=4537,3056163|newspaper=The Portsmouth Times|date=28 May 1976|page=12|title=Claims In Disaster Denied}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wvculture.org/history/wvhs1504.html |title=The Collapse of the Silver Bridge-by Chris LeRose |publisher=Wvculture.org |accessdate=2009-07-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130830051225/http://www.wvculture.org/history/wvhs1504.html |archivedate=2013-08-30 }}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\n[[Image:Kittanning Citizen's Bridge.JPG|thumb|200px|Kittanning Citizens Bridge]]\nAside from a few opening scenes filmed in [[Washington, D.C.]], most of the motion picture was filmed in the areas of [[Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania|Pittsburgh]] and [[Kittanning, Pennsylvania|Kittanning]] in [[Pennsylvania]]. The scenes of Gere sitting on a park bench are on the [[University of Pittsburgh]] campus.{{sfn|Tiech|2014|p=72}} Road montages were filmed on [[Pennsylvania Route 28]], and the [[Chicago]] scenes are completely shot in downtown Pittsburgh\u2019s [[Mellon Square]] and Trinity Churchyard environs as well as the entrance to the Duquesne Club. The \"Chemical Plant\" featured in the movie is actually a power station owned by Reliant Energy in Elrama, Pennsylvania. The Avalon Motor Inn is in [[Eighty Four, Pennsylvania]], though scenes set indoors were built as separate sets, as the inn's atmosphere could not accommodate production.{{sfn|Tiech|2014|p=73}} Point Pleasant scenes were shot in [[Kittanning, Pennsylvania]].  The hospital scenes were filmed at St. Frances Medical Center which is now the site of Children's Hospital of Pittsburgh. \nThe collapse of the [[Silver Bridge]] was actually filmed at the [[Kittanning Citizens Bridge]] in downtown Kittanning. Scenes shot at Gordon Smallwood\u2019s house were filmed in Washington County on [[Pennsylvania Route 917]]. Pittsburgh\u2019s [[Allegheny County Airport]] serves as backdrop for the airfield scenes. Despite this relocation, several police officers from Point Pleasant appeared as extras.<ref>{{cite web |author=Spiderweb 2000 Solutions |url=http://www.mothmanmuseum.com/MothmanLives/mothmanmovie/register/pointpleasantregister1.html |title=Point Pleasant Register \u2013 Mothman |publisher=Mothmanmuseum.com |accessdate=2009-07-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090717004446/http://www.mothmanmuseum.com/MothmanLives/mothmanmovie/register/pointpleasantregister1.html |archivedate=2009-07-17 }}</ref>\n\n===Music===\nThe film's musical score was composed by the creative lab [[tomandandy]]. On January 22, 2002. [[Lakeshore Records]] released a two-disc edition of the soundtrack.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.barnesandnoble.com/w/the-mothman-prophecies-king-black-acid-and-the-womb-star-orchestra/6176821?ean=780163369427 | title = The Mothman Prophecies Original Motion Picture Soundtrack | publisher = Barnes & Noble | accessdate = 2013-02-06 }}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = The Mothman Prophecies: Music From the Motion Picture Disc 1\n| type       = [[Film score]]\n| artist     = Various Artists\n| cover      = TheMothmanSoundtrack.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = January 22, 2002\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      =\n| length     = 44:05\n| label      = [[Lakeshore Records]]\n| producer   = [[Cliff Eidelman]]<br />[[tomandandy]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed       = no\n| headline        = ''The Mothman Prophecies: Music From the Motion Picture Disc 1''\n| total_length    = 44:05\n| title1          = Half Light (single)\n| length1         = 4:23\n| title2          = Wake Up #37\n| length2         = 5:37\n| title3          = Haunted\n| length3         = 5:03\n| title4          = One and Only\n| length4         = 1:59\n| title5          = Collage\n| length5         = 1:05\n| title6          = Great Spaces\n| length6         = 5:19\n| title7          = Rolling Under\n| length7         = 5:26\n| title8          = Half Life\n| length8         = 4:13\n| title9          = Soul Systems Burn\n| length9         = 5:35\n| title10         = Half Light (tail credit)\n| length10        = 6:46\n}}\n\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = The Mothman Prophecies: Music From the Motion Picture Disc 2\n| type       = [[Film score]]\n| artist     = [[tomandandy]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = January 22, 2002\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      =\n| length     = 58:03\n| label      = Lakeshore Records\n| producer   =\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed       = no\n| headline        = ''The Mothman Prophecies: Music From the Motion Picture Disc 2''\n| total_length    = 58:03\n| title1          = Movement 1: Composed of 12 Members/ Retrace/ A New Home/ MRI/ Welcome To Point Pleasant\n| length1         = 8:05\n| title2          = Movement 2: Point Pleasant/ Seeing Strange Things/ It's a Voice and It's Saying, Do Not Be Afraid/ He's Wrong/ Denver 9\n| length2         = 7:32\n| title3          = Movement 3: I Had a Dream Like That/ Not From Human Vocal Chords/ Zone Of Fear/ Ring Ring/ Leek/ Leek Wouldn't See Me\n| length3         = 9:53\n| title4          = Movement 4: All At Once, I Understand, Everything/ Do You Know That Woman?/ The Tape Reveals/ We Are Not Allowed To Know\n| length4         = 7:36\n| title5          = Movement 5: It's How I Ended Up Here/ Airport/ I Have To Go\n| length5         = 4:25\n| title6          = Movement 6: We Have Dinner At 6, And We Open Presents At 8/ 12:00 Call\n| length6         = 3:51\n| title7          = Movement 7: The Bridge\n| length7         = 8:21\n| title8          = Movement 8: Mirror Drone/ John's Theme/ Cellos\n| length8         = 9:40\n}}\n\n==Release==\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Mothman statue in Point Pleasant, West Virginia.jpg|150px|thumb|A Mothman statue in [[Point Pleasant, West Virginia]], the community that became a focal point in promotion.]] -->\nAfter the film was theatrically released on January 25, 2002, writer [[Brad Steiger]] observed Point Pleasant became a focal point for its promotion.{{sfn|Steiger|2012}} Marketing in television and posters emphasized claims it was \"based on true events\", despite the supernatural premise and Pellington's acknowledgement that the account was reframed as a fictional narrative.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ew.com/article/2002/02/01/how-real-mothman-prophecies/ |title=How real is 'The Mothman Prophecies'? |last=Hiatt |first=Brian |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=February 1, 2002 |accessdate=August 23, 2017}}</ref> \n\nOn June 4th 2002, a [[DVD region code#1|Region 1]] edition of the motion picture was released on DVD. Special features included [[audio commentary]] by Pellington, a documentary entitled ''Search for the Mothman'', and the featurette \"Day by Day: A Director's Journey \u2013 The Road In\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/dvd/review/the-mothman-prophecies |title=The Mothman Prophecies |last=Gonzalez |first=Ed |work=[[Slant Magazine]] |date=May 6, 2003 |accessdate=August 23, 2017}}</ref> In [[DVD region code#2|Region 2]], a DVD was published also including ''Search for the Mothman'' as well as interviews with Gere, Linney and Patton.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2002/10/21/the_mothman_prophecies_2002_dvd_review.shtml |title=The Mothman Prophecies DVD (2002) |last=Haflidason |first=Almar |work=[[BBC]] |accessdate=August 23, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Critical response===\nAmong mainstream critics in the U.S., the film received mixed reviews.<ref name=\"meta\">[https://metacritic.com/movie/the-mothman-prophecies The Mothman Prophecies]. [[Metacritic]]. CNET Networks. Retrieved 2013-02-06.</ref> [[Rotten Tomatoes]] reported that 52% of 138 sampled critics gave the film a positive review, with an average score of 5.5 out of 10.<ref>[https://rottentomatoes.com/m/mothman_prophecies/ The Mothman Prophecies (2002)]. [[Rotten Tomatoes]]. IGN Entertainment. Retrieved July 24, 2018.</ref> At [[Metacritic]], which assigns a [[weighted mean|weighted average]] out of 100 to critics' reviews, ''The Mothman Prophecies'' received a score of 52 based on 32 reviews.<ref name=\"meta\" /> In 2003, the film won the ''Best Sound Editing: Music in a Feature Film'' award from the society of the [[Motion Picture Sound Editors]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mpse.org/goldenreels/pastawards.html |title=Past Golden Reel Awards |publisher=MPSE.org |date= |accessdate=2013-02-06}}</ref>\n\n[[Roger Ebert]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' gave it two stars out of four, calling it unfocused, but praised the direction by Mark Pellington \"whose command of camera, pacing and the overall effect is so good, it deserves a better screenplay.\"<ref>{{cite web| url=https://rogerebert.com/reviews/the-mothman-prophecies-2002 |title=The Mothman Prophecies |work=Rogerebert.com |last=Ebert |first=Roger |date=January 25, 2002 |accessdate=August 23, 2017 }}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'' critic Elvis Mitchell judged it \"hushed and smooth\" but \"little more than an adequate shard of winter-doldrums genre fare\".<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9502E1DC1F3BF936A15752C0A9649C8B63&mcubz=3 |title=FILM REVIEW; Mysteries Multiply In Spooky Adventures |work=[[The New York Times]] |last=Mitchell |first=Elvis |date=January 25, 2002 |accessdate=August 23, 2017 }}</ref> ''[[The Washington Post]]''{{'}}s Stephen Hunter dismissed it as \"all buzz: It's camerawork on the verge of a meltdown and weird music in search of a composer\", and joked seeing it \"is like getting mugged in an alley by an especially thuggish crew of [[Method actor]]s\".<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/2002/01/25/mothman-gere-in-overdrive/3b81d989-63b4-47ad-88ea-0d6e3dc612a7/ |title='Mothman': Gere in Overdrive |work=[[The Washington Post]] |last=Hunter |first=Stephen |date=January 25, 2002 |accessdate=August 23, 2017 }}</ref> In ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'', Robert Koehler claimed it \"wanders away from its sustained atmospherics into silly expository detours\".<ref>{{cite web| url=https://variety.com/2002/film/reviews/the-mothman-prophecies-1200551819/ |title=Review: 'The Mothman Prophecies' |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |last=Koehler |first=Robert |date=January 18, 2002 |accessdate=August 23, 2017 }}</ref> For ''[[The Guardian]]'', Bob Rickard defended it as \"an intelligent and creative exploration of the slippery, dream-like world of those who 'get too close' \".<ref name=\"Rickard\"/>\n\n===Box office===\n''The Mothman Prophecies'' opened at the U.S. box office on January 25, 2002, earning $11,208,851 in its first weekend failing to enter the top five grossing films.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://boxofficemojo.com/weekend/chart/?yr=2002&wknd=04&p=.htm |title=January 25\u201327, 2002 Weekend |publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=2013-02-06}}</ref> It eventually went on to garner $35,746,370 in the U.S., and $19,411,169 in foreign markets for a worldwide total of $55,157,539.<ref name=\"BoxOfficeMojo\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* {{cite book |last=Barker |first=Gray |title=The Silver Bridge: The Classic Mothman Tale |year=2008 |publisher=BookSurge Publishing |isbn=978-1-439-20427-6}}\n* {{cite book |last=Coleman |first=Loren |title=Mothman and Other Curious Encounters |year=2002 |publisher=Paraview Press |isbn=978-1-931-04434-9}}\n* {{cite book |last=Guiley |first=Rosemary |title=Monsters of West Virginia: Mysterious Creatures in the Mountain State |year=2012 |publisher=Stackpole Books |isbn=978-0-811-71028-2}}\n* {{cite book |last=Horsley |first=Jason |title=The Secret Life of Movies: Schizophrenic and Shamanic Journeys in American Cinema |year=2009 |location=Jefferson, North Carolina and London |publisher=McFarland |isbn=0786454628 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Kay |first=Gregory |title=Wings In Darkness |year=2013 |publisher=CreateSpace Independent Publishing Platform |isbn=978-1-481-81142-2}}\n* {{cite book |last=Meehan |first=Paul |chapter=Alien ESP |title=Cinema of the Psychic Realm: A Critical Survey |year=2009 |location=Jefferson, North Carolina and London |publisher=McFarland |isbn=0786454741|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Steiger |first=Brad |chapter=Mothman |title=Real Nightmares (Book 8): Phantoms, Apparitions and Ghosts |year=2012 |location= |publisher=Visible Ink Press |isbn=1578594383 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Tiech |first=John |title=Pittsburgh Film and Television |year=2014 |publisher=Arcadia Publishing |isbn=1439644500 |ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.sonypictures.com/homevideo/catalog/catalogDetail_DVD043396093263.html}}\n* {{IMDb title|id=0265349|title=The Mothman Prophecies}}\n* {{Amg movie|258955|The Mothman Prophecies}}\n* {{Rotten-tomatoes|mothman_prophecies|title=The Mothman Prophecies}}\n* {{metacritic film|the-mothman-prophecies|title=The Mothman Prophecies}}\n* {{mojo title|id=mothmanprophecies|title=The Mothman Prophecies}}\n\n{{Mark Pellington}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mothman Prophecies}}\n[[Category:2002 films]]\n[[Category:2002 horror films]]\n[[Category:2000s thriller films]]\n[[Category:American mystery films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films based on American novels]]\n[[Category:Films based on mystery novels]]\n[[Category:American films based on actual events]]\n[[Category:Films based on urban legends]]\n[[Category:Lakeshore Entertainment films]]\n[[Category:Mothman]]\n[[Category:Screen Gems films]]\n[[Category:American supernatural horror films]]\n[[Category:Films set in Pittsburgh]]\n[[Category:Films set in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Films set in West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Pittsburgh]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Mark Pellington]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Cliff Eidelman]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Tomandandy]]\n[[Category:Fiction about cryptids]]\n[[Category:2000s psychological horror films]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Tom Rosenberg]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Gary Lucchesi]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Mothman Prophecies\n| image          = Mothman prophecies poster.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Mark Pellington]]\n| producer       = [[Gary W. Goldstein]]<br />[[Gary Lucchesi]]<br />[[Tom Rosenberg]]\n| screenplay     = [[Richard Hatem]]\n| based on       = ''[[The Mothman Prophecies]]'' by [[John Keel]]\n| starring       = [[Richard Gere]]<br />[[Laura Linney]]<br />[[Will Patton]]<br />[[Debra Messing]]<br />[[Lucinda Jenney]]<br />[[Alan Bates]]\n| music          = [[Cliff Eidelman]]<br />[[tomandandy]]\n| cinematography = Fred Murphy\n| editing        = [[Brian Berdan]]\n| studio         = [[Lakeshore Entertainment]] \n| distributor    = [[Screen Gems]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2002|1|25}}\n| runtime        = 119 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $32 million<ref name=BoxOfficeMojo>{{cite web |url=https://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=mothmanprophecies.htm |title=The Mothman Prophecies (2002)|publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=2013-02-06}}</ref>\n| gross          = $55.1 million<ref name=\"BoxOfficeMojo\"/>\n}}\n\n'''''The Mothman Prophecies''''' is a 2002 American [[supernatural horror]]-[[mystery film]] directed by [[Mark Pellington]], and starring [[Richard Gere]] and [[Laura Linney]]. Based on the 1975 [[The Mothman Prophecies|book of the same name]] by [[parapsychology|parapsychologist]] and [[Charles Fort|Fortean]] author [[John Keel]], the screenplay was written by [[Richard Hatem]]. \n\nThe story follows John Klein (Gere), a reporter who researches the legend of the [[Mothman]]. Still shaken by the death of his wife, two years earlier in a mysterious accident. Klein is sent to cover a news piece and ends up inexplicably finding himself in [[Point Pleasant, West Virginia]], where there have been sightings of an unusual creature and other unexplained phenomena. As he becomes increasingly drawn into mysterious forces at work, he hopes they can reconnect him to his wife, while the local sheriff (Linney) becomes concerned about his obsessions.\n\nThe film claims to be based on actual events that occurred between November 1966 and December 1967 in Point Pleasant, as described by Keel. It was shot in  [[Pittsburgh]] and [[Kittanning, Pennsylvania]] and was released to mixed reviews.\n\n==Plot==\n''[[Washington Post]]'' columnist John Klein and his wife Mary are involved in an accident when Mary swerves to avoid a black, flying figure. John survives the crash unscathed, but Mary is hospitalized. After Mary dies of an unrelated [[glioblastoma|brain tumor]], John discovers mysterious drawings of the creature that she had created whilst in hospital.\n\nTwo years later, John becomes lost in [[West Virginia]] and inexplicably finds himself in [[Point Pleasant, West Virginia|Point Pleasant]], hundreds of miles off his route. Driving in the middle of the night, his car breaks down; and he walks to a nearby house to get help. The owner, Gordon Smallwood, reacts violently to John's appearance and holds him at gunpoint. Local police officer Connie Mills defuses the situation while Gordon explains that this is the third consecutive night John has knocked on his door at 2:30 AM, asking to use a phone, much to John's confusion. John stays at a local motel and considers how he ended up so far from his original destination.\n\nOfficer Mills mentions to John that many strange things have been occurring in the past few weeks and that people report seeing a large winged creature like a giant [[moth]] with red eyes. She also tells John about a strange dream she had, in which the words \"Wake up, Number 37\" were spoken to her. During a conversation one day, Gordon reveals to John that he has heard voices coming from his sink telling him that, in [[Denver]], \"99 will die\". While discussing the day's events at a local diner, John notices that the news is showing the story of an airplane crash in Denver that killed all 99 passengers aboard. The next night Gordon frantically explains that the voices in his head emanate from a being named Indrid Cold.\n\nLater that night Gordon calls John and says that he is standing next to someone named Indrid Cold. While John keeps Cold on the line, Officer Mills checks on Gordon. Cold answers John's questions, including ones he could not possibly know the answers to, convincing John that Cold is a supernatural being. This episode starts a string of supernatural calls to John's motel room. One tells him that there will be a great tragedy on the [[Ohio River]]. Later John receives a call from Gordon and rushes to his home to check on him. He finds Gordon outside, dead from [[Hypothermia|exposure]].\n\nJohn becomes obsessed with the being dubbed the Mothman. He meets an expert on the subject, Alexander Leek, who explains its nature and discourages John from becoming further involved. However, when John learns the [[Governor of West Virginia|Governor]] plans to tour a chemical plant located on the Ohio River the following day, he becomes convinced the tragedy will occur there. Officer Mills and the governor ignore his warnings, and nothing happens during the tour. Soon afterwards, John receives a mysterious message that instructs him to await a call from his deceased wife Mary back in [[Georgetown (Washington, D.C.)|Georgetown]], and he returns home.\n\nOn [[Christmas Eve]], Officer Mills calls and convinces him to ignore the phone call from \"Mary\", return to Point Pleasant, and join her. Though anguished, John agrees. As John reaches the [[Silver Bridge]], a malfunctioning traffic light causes traffic congestion. As John walks onto the bridge to investigate, the bolts and supports of the bridge strain. The bridge comes apart, and John realizes that the prophesied tragedy on the Ohio River was about the bridge. As the bridge collapses, Officer Mills' car falls into the water. John jumps in after her and pulls her from the river and up to safety. As the two sit on the back of an ambulance, they see that 36 people have been killed, making Connie the \"number 37\" from her dream. The cause of the bridge collapse was never fully determined. Although the Mothman has been sighted in other parts of the world, it was never seen again in Point Pleasant.\n\n==Cast==\n[[File:Richardgere.jpg|thumb|upright|right|Lead actor Richard Gere who portrayed the protagonist John Klein.]]\n* [[Richard Gere]] as John Klein\n* [[Laura Linney]] as Connie Mills\n* [[Will Patton]] as Gordon Smallwood\n* [[Debra Messing]] as Mary Klein\n* [[Lucinda Jenney]] as Denise Smallwood\n* [[Alan Bates]] as Alexander Leek\n* [[David Eigenberg]] as Ed Fleischman\n* Bob Tracey as Cyrus Bills\n* [[Mark Pellington]] as Indrid Cold \"The Mothman\" (voice)\n\n==Themes and interpretations==\n[[File:Mothman2.jpg |200px |left |thumb |Film critics have interpreted the film's portrayal of [[Mothman]] as demonic.]]\nWriter Paul Meehan judged the film's explanation of the Mothman to be a \"confused mish-mosh of [[science fiction]] and [[demonology]]\" and likened it to the television series ''[[The X-Files]]'', though preserving Keel's \"breathless hysteria\".{{sfn|Meehan|2009|p=130}} Meehan remarked that \"Aliens spouting prophetic utterances are rare in UFO literature\".{{sfn|Meehan|2009|p=130}}\n\nIn contrast to Meehan, author Jason Horsley declared ''The Mothman Prophecies'' \"probably the most effective depiction of demonic forces at work\" in U.S. cinema.{{sfn|Horsley|2009|p=197}} Horsley assessed its approach to the Mothman legend as depicting a \"schizophrenic nature of reality\", fulfilling a \"revelation\" purpose in [[horror film]], as it \"strips away the comfortable veneer of consensus reality to reveal the seething abyss of irrationality\".{{sfn|Horsley|2009|p=197}} Horsley argued the film's Mothman arrives from a foreign dimension, but being without \"physical existence\", it is also a product of the minds of Point Pleasant's citizens, based on \"formless and impersonal energy\".{{sfn|Horsley|2009|p=198}} The Mothman, identified by Horsley as \"emissary of the [[Id, ego and super-ego|Id]]\", is depicted in the film as being as natural as electricity or gravity.{{sfn|Horsley|2009|p=198}}\n\n==Production==\n[[Carl Franklin]] was originally attached to direct Richard Hatem's [[spec script]] before [[Mark Pellington]] was hired.<ref>{{cite news|author=Petrikin, Chris|title=Fox puts Armitage in Doud\u2019s \u2018Body\u2019|url=https://variety.com/1999/film/news/fox-puts-armitage-in-doud-s-body-1117500041/|work=Variety|date=May 5, 1999|accessdate=July 25, 2015}}</ref> Pellington rejected numerous screenplay drafts as literal interpretations of Keel's book, and wished to explore psychological drama in UFO witnesses.<ref name=\"Rickard\">{{cite web|last=Rickard |first=Bob |title=The moth man cometh |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2002/feb/22/artsfeatures3 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=February 22, 2002 |accessdate=August 23, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn reality, 46 people died in the collapse of the [[Silver Bridge]], not 36 as depicted in the film. The motion picture's claim at the end credits of the collapse of the Silver Bridge never being explained is false; the incident was found to be caused by the failure of an [[Eyebar|eye-bar]] in a suspension chain in 1971, well before the publication of the book on which the film is based, let alone the film.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.ca/newspapers?id=cJ1eAAAAIBAJ&sjid=MVMNAAAAIBAJ&pg=4537,3056163|newspaper=The Portsmouth Times|date=28 May 1976|page=12|title=Claims In Disaster Denied}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wvculture.org/history/wvhs1504.html |title=The Collapse of the Silver Bridge-by Chris LeRose |publisher=Wvculture.org |accessdate=2009-07-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130830051225/http://www.wvculture.org/history/wvhs1504.html |archivedate=2013-08-30 }}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\n[[Image:Kittanning Citizen's Bridge.JPG|thumb|200px|Kittanning Citizens Bridge]]\nAside from a few opening scenes filmed in [[Washington, D.C.]], most of the motion picture was filmed in the areas of [[Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania|Pittsburgh]] and [[Kittanning, Pennsylvania|Kittanning]] in [[Pennsylvania]]. The scenes of Gere sitting on a park bench are on the [[University of Pittsburgh]] campus.{{sfn|Tiech|2014|p=72}} Road montages were filmed on [[Pennsylvania Route 28]], and the [[Chicago]] scenes are completely shot in downtown Pittsburgh\u2019s [[Mellon Square]] and Trinity Churchyard environs as well as the entrance to the Duquesne Club. The \"Chemical Plant\" featured in the movie is actually a power station owned by Reliant Energy in Elrama, Pennsylvania. The Avalon Motor Inn is in [[Eighty Four, Pennsylvania]], though scenes set indoors were built as separate sets, as the inn's atmosphere could not accommodate production.{{sfn|Tiech|2014|p=73}} Point Pleasant scenes were shot in [[Kittanning, Pennsylvania]].  The hospital scenes were filmed at St. Frances Medical Center which is now the site of Children's Hospital of Pittsburgh. \nThe collapse of the [[Silver Bridge]] was actually filmed at the [[Kittanning Citizens Bridge]] in downtown Kittanning. Scenes shot at Gordon Smallwood\u2019s house were filmed in Washington County on [[Pennsylvania Route 917]]. Pittsburgh\u2019s [[Allegheny County Airport]] serves as backdrop for the airfield scenes. Despite this relocation, several police officers from Point Pleasant appeared as extras.<ref>{{cite web |author=Spiderweb 2000 Solutions |url=http://www.mothmanmuseum.com/MothmanLives/mothmanmovie/register/pointpleasantregister1.html |title=Point Pleasant Register \u2013 Mothman |publisher=Mothmanmuseum.com |accessdate=2009-07-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090717004446/http://www.mothmanmuseum.com/MothmanLives/mothmanmovie/register/pointpleasantregister1.html |archivedate=2009-07-17 }}</ref>\n\n===Music===\nThe film's musical score was composed by the creative lab [[tomandandy]]. On January 22, 2002. [[Lakeshore Records]] released a two-disc edition of the soundtrack.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.barnesandnoble.com/w/the-mothman-prophecies-king-black-acid-and-the-womb-star-orchestra/6176821?ean=780163369427 | title = The Mothman Prophecies Original Motion Picture Soundtrack | publisher = Barnes & Noble | accessdate = 2013-02-06 }}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = The Mothman Prophecies: Music From the Motion Picture Disc 1\n| type       = [[Film score]]\n| artist     = Various Artists\n| cover      = TheMothmanSoundtrack.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = January 22, 2002\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      =\n| length     = 44:05\n| label      = [[Lakeshore Records]]\n| producer   = [[Cliff Eidelman]]<br />[[tomandandy]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed       = no\n| headline        = ''The Mothman Prophecies: Music From the Motion Picture Disc 1''\n| total_length    = 44:05\n| title1          = Half Light (single)\n| length1         = 4:23\n| title2          = Wake Up #37\n| length2         = 5:37\n| title3          = Haunted\n| length3         = 5:03\n| title4          = One and Only\n| length4         = 1:59\n| title5          = Collage\n| length5         = 1:05\n| title6          = Great Spaces\n| length6         = 5:19\n| title7          = Rolling Under\n| length7         = 5:26\n| title8          = Half Life\n| length8         = 4:13\n| title9          = Soul Systems Burn\n| length9         = 5:35\n| title10         = Half Light (tail credit)\n| length10        = 6:46\n}}\n\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = The Mothman Prophecies: Music From the Motion Picture Disc 2\n| type       = [[Film score]]\n| artist     = [[tomandandy]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = January 22, 2002\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      =\n| length     = 58:03\n| label      = Lakeshore Records\n| producer   =\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed       = no\n| headline        = ''The Mothman Prophecies: Music From the Motion Picture Disc 2''\n| total_length    = 58:03\n| title1          = Movement 1: Composed of 12 Members/ Retrace/ A New Home/ MRI/ Welcome To Point Pleasant\n| length1         = 8:05\n| title2          = Movement 2: Point Pleasant/ Seeing Strange Things/ It's a Voice and It's Saying, Do Not Be Afraid/ He's Wrong/ Denver 9\n| length2         = 7:32\n| title3          = Movement 3: I Had a Dream Like That/ Not From Human Vocal Chords/ Zone Of Fear/ Ring Ring/ Leek/ Leek Wouldn't See Me\n| length3         = 9:53\n| title4          = Movement 4: All At Once, I Understand, Everything/ Do You Know That Woman?/ The Tape Reveals/ We Are Not Allowed To Know\n| length4         = 7:36\n| title5          = Movement 5: It's How I Ended Up Here/ Airport/ I Have To Go\n| length5         = 4:25\n| title6          = Movement 6: We Have Dinner At 6, And We Open Presents At 8/ 12:00 Call\n| length6         = 3:51\n| title7          = Movement 7: The Bridge\n| length7         = 8:21\n| title8          = Movement 8: Mirror Drone/ John's Theme/ Cellos\n| length8         = 9:40\n}}\n\n==Release==\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Mothman statue in Point Pleasant, West Virginia.jpg|150px|thumb|A Mothman statue in [[Point Pleasant, West Virginia]], the community that became a focal point in promotion.]] -->\nAfter the film was theatrically released on January 25, 2002, writer [[Brad Steiger]] observed Point Pleasant became a focal point for its promotion.{{sfn|Steiger|2012}} Marketing in television and posters emphasized claims it was \"based on true events\", despite the supernatural premise and Pellington's acknowledgement that the account was reframed as a fictional narrative.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ew.com/article/2002/02/01/how-real-mothman-prophecies/ |title=How real is 'The Mothman Prophecies'? |last=Hiatt |first=Brian |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=February 1, 2002 |accessdate=August 23, 2017}}</ref> \n\nOn June 4th 2002, a [[DVD region code#1|Region 1]] edition of the motion picture was released on DVD. Special features included [[audio commentary]] by Pellington, a documentary entitled ''Search for the Mothman'', and the featurette \"Day by Day: A Director's Journey \u2013 The Road In\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/dvd/review/the-mothman-prophecies |title=The Mothman Prophecies |last=Gonzalez |first=Ed |work=[[Slant Magazine]] |date=May 6, 2003 |accessdate=August 23, 2017}}</ref> In [[DVD region code#2|Region 2]], a DVD was published also including ''Search for the Mothman'' as well as interviews with Gere, Linney and Patton.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2002/10/21/the_mothman_prophecies_2002_dvd_review.shtml |title=The Mothman Prophecies DVD (2002) |last=Haflidason |first=Almar |work=[[BBC]] |accessdate=August 23, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Critical response===\nAmong mainstream critics in the U.S., the film received mixed reviews.<ref name=\"meta\">[https://metacritic.com/movie/the-mothman-prophecies The Mothman Prophecies]. [[Metacritic]]. CNET Networks. Retrieved 2013-02-06.</ref> [[Rotten Tomatoes]] reported that 52% of 138 sampled critics gave the film a positive review, with an average score of 5.5 out of 10.<ref>[https://rottentomatoes.com/m/mothman_prophecies/ The Mothman Prophecies (2002)]. [[Rotten Tomatoes]]. IGN Entertainment. Retrieved July 24, 2018.</ref> At [[Metacritic]], which assigns a [[weighted mean|weighted average]] out of 100 to critics' reviews, ''The Mothman Prophecies'' received a score of 52 based on 32 reviews.<ref name=\"meta\" /> In 2003, the film won the ''Best Sound Editing: Music in a Feature Film'' award from the society of the [[Motion Picture Sound Editors]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mpse.org/goldenreels/pastawards.html |title=Past Golden Reel Awards |publisher=MPSE.org |date= |accessdate=2013-02-06}}</ref>\n\n[[Roger Ebert]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' gave it two stars out of four, calling it unfocused, but praised the direction by Mark Pellington \"whose command of camera, pacing and the overall effect is so good, it deserves a better screenplay.\"<ref>{{cite web| url=https://rogerebert.com/reviews/the-mothman-prophecies-2002 |title=The Mothman Prophecies |work=Rogerebert.com |last=Ebert |first=Roger |date=January 25, 2002 |accessdate=August 23, 2017 }}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'' critic Elvis Mitchell judged it \"hushed and smooth\" but \"little more than an adequate shard of winter-doldrums genre fare\".<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9502E1DC1F3BF936A15752C0A9649C8B63&mcubz=3 |title=FILM REVIEW; Mysteries Multiply In Spooky Adventures |work=[[The New York Times]] |last=Mitchell |first=Elvis |date=January 25, 2002 |accessdate=August 23, 2017 }}</ref> ''[[The Washington Post]]''{{'}}s Stephen Hunter dismissed it as \"all buzz: It's camerawork on the verge of a meltdown and weird music in search of a composer\", and joked seeing it \"is like getting mugged in an alley by an especially thuggish crew of [[Method actor]]s\".<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/2002/01/25/mothman-gere-in-overdrive/3b81d989-63b4-47ad-88ea-0d6e3dc612a7/ |title='Mothman': Gere in Overdrive |work=[[The Washington Post]] |last=Hunter |first=Stephen |date=January 25, 2002 |accessdate=August 23, 2017 }}</ref> In ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'', Robert Koehler claimed it \"wanders away from its sustained atmospherics into silly expository detours\".<ref>{{cite web| url=https://variety.com/2002/film/reviews/the-mothman-prophecies-1200551819/ |title=Review: 'The Mothman Prophecies' |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |last=Koehler |first=Robert |date=January 18, 2002 |accessdate=August 23, 2017 }}</ref> For ''[[The Guardian]]'', Bob Rickard defended it as \"an intelligent and creative exploration of the slippery, dream-like world of those who 'get too close' \".<ref name=\"Rickard\"/>\n\n===Box office===\n''The Mothman Prophecies'' opened at the U.S. box office on January 25, 2002, earning $11,208,851 in its first weekend failing to enter the top five grossing films.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://boxofficemojo.com/weekend/chart/?yr=2002&wknd=04&p=.htm |title=January 25\u201327, 2002 Weekend |publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=2013-02-06}}</ref> It eventually went on to garner $35,746,370 in the U.S., and $19,411,169 in foreign markets for a worldwide total of $55,157,539.<ref name=\"BoxOfficeMojo\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* {{cite book |last=Barker |first=Gray |title=The Silver Bridge: The Classic Mothman Tale |year=2008 |publisher=BookSurge Publishing |isbn=978-1-439-20427-6}}\n* {{cite book |last=Coleman |first=Loren |title=Mothman and Other Curious Encounters |year=2002 |publisher=Paraview Press |isbn=978-1-931-04434-9}}\n* {{cite book |last=Guiley |first=Rosemary |title=Monsters of West Virginia: Mysterious Creatures in the Mountain State |year=2012 |publisher=Stackpole Books |isbn=978-0-811-71028-2}}\n* {{cite book |last=Horsley |first=Jason |title=The Secret Life of Movies: Schizophrenic and Shamanic Journeys in American Cinema |year=2009 |location=Jefferson, North Carolina and London |publisher=McFarland |isbn=0786454628 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Kay |first=Gregory |title=Wings In Darkness |year=2013 |publisher=CreateSpace Independent Publishing Platform |isbn=978-1-481-81142-2}}\n* {{cite book |last=Meehan |first=Paul |chapter=Alien ESP |title=Cinema of the Psychic Realm: A Critical Survey |year=2009 |location=Jefferson, North Carolina and London |publisher=McFarland |isbn=0786454741|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Steiger |first=Brad |chapter=Mothman |title=Real Nightmares (Book 8): Phantoms, Apparitions and Ghosts |year=2012 |location= |publisher=Visible Ink Press |isbn=157859438